    <title>Combined summary - [BIP] Normalized Transaction IDs</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T21:02:15.040926+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-May/008177.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In the Bitcoin community, there have been discussions about addressing transaction malleability, which refers to the ability of attackers to modify transaction details without changing the validity of the transaction. Several proposals have been made to address this issue, including the use of normalized transaction IDs that remove the scriptSig before computing the hash. This ensures that only data whose integrity is guaranteed by signatures influences the hash and solves the problem of transaction malleability.Christian Decker, a Bitcoin developer, has proposed a Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP) to normalize transaction IDs and address transaction malleability. The proposal aims to simplify higher level protocols by creating an alias used alongside legacy transaction IDs to address outputs in transactions. The normalized ID is calculated by removing the scriptSig before computing the hash, ensuring that only data whose integrity is guaranteed by the signatures influences the hash. This would require a hard fork to implement and upgrade, but Decker believes it would be a valuable addition to Bitcoin's functionality.The discussion also covers the use of CHECKLOCKTIMEVERIFY, the doubling of the UTXO database, and concerns about the deployment costs associated with upgrading every single piece of Bitcoin software on the planet. Other contributors suggest modifications to the proposal, such as eliminating the need for a second index by requiring an SPV proof of the spending transaction to be included with legacy transactions and incorporating the height in the scriptSig for all transactions. There are also discussions about the advantages and disadvantages of the proposed SIGHASH change versus the normalized transaction ID.Pieter Wuille argues that a soft fork approach is better and suggests a solution that involves replacing scriptSigs in inputs with the empty string and using ntxids in sighashes rather than the full txid. Another proposal discussed was the use of OP_CHECKAWESOMESIG, which involves using the current hashes to reference semantically identical transactions and requires either computing the normalized transaction ID on the fly or storing it alongside the UTXO. There were also discussions about how to address the issue of BIP 34, which sets a new block height rule for the Bitcoin network and could potentially enable replay attacks.Furthermore, there are discussions about the size of a mapping legacy ID to normalized ID and bundling this change with other changes that require a hard-fork may be a good idea. A generic hard-fork rollout mechanism proposal is suggested, and the reference client can be updated to use version 2 transactions by default. If &gt;75% of the transactions by weight are version 2 in blocks 375000 to 385000, then the community is considered to support the hard fork. Devs update the reference client to produce version 4 blocks and version 3 transactions if the community supports the hard fork. If 750 of the last 1000 blocks are version 4 or higher, blocks with transactions of less than version 3 in version 4 blocks are rejected. If 950 of the last 1000 blocks are version 4 or higher, blocks with transactions of less than version 3 in all blocks are rejected. Lastly, if 1000 of the last 1000 blocks are version 4 or higher and the difficulty retarget has just happened, the hard fork rule is activated which hard forks legacy nodes off the chain.In conclusion, there are various proposals being considered for normalizing transaction IDs to address transaction malleability and facilitate higher level protocols. These proposals may require multiple BIPs, and some suggest implementing proposals before submitting them for consideration. There are also discussions about the use of legacy references versus normalized transaction IDs and the feasibility of replacing all txids in the entire blockchain with their normalized versions.</summary>
